title: For Sale:  AR15 Anderson lower/Colt surplus M16 upper
postcontent:
If you're looking for an AR15 with a battle-worn look that runs reliably, this may be the rifle for you!

This rifle started life as a "spare parts" build or "Franken" AR, but it has turned out to be a pretty nice little rifle.  The receiver is an Anderson Arms lower, finished off with an assortment of quality lower parts that were sitting in my parts bin.  Everything works as it should.  The buffer tube is a commercial-spec carbine tube, but the Magpul stock that is on it is a fixed-style stock they make for the carbine tubes.  To make the lower look a little more battle-worn to match the upper, I spent a lot of time putting wear on all the parts and places that get beat up on a real military lower receiver.  Everything functions like new, but the lower looks like it has been beat around a military armory for a decade or two, just like the Colt upper.

The upper receiver started as a Colt surplus M16 upper receiver, and was completed with new A2 sight parts and ejection port cover.  It's a nice worn Colt gray color.  I added a Sota Arms 16" 5.56 barrel, A2 front sight gas block and A2 flash hider.  The bolt and bolt carrier are from Shadow Ops.

Furniture is all from Magpul's MOE line.  The front handguard and the grip are from the "slim line," and the stock is a fixed stock designed for carbine buffer tubes.  It's all in Stealth Gray color.  The rifle also comes with one Magpul black M3 30-round PMAG.

Not pictured, but also included are a picatinny rail adapter for the carry handle that allows you to mount a scope, and a partial box of Fiocchi brass .223 rounds.

This rifle has only been shot once to function check it and make sure everything ran right.  After building it, I just realized I didn't really need it.  I prefer shooting my registered short-barreled .300 BLK and .458 SOCOM AR15s more than a standard 16" 5.56 rifle.  But it's a good rifle, and if it doesn't sell, it will live happily in my gun chest.

Mainly looking to sell, but if you have any interesting trades to offer, drop me an message.  Might consider trades for the right 1911, but overall I'd prefer to sell outright.  Also feel free to make an offer if you don't think the price is right.

title: For Sale:  BULLET PROOF VEST GUY DOES NOT LIE!!
location: OKC Metro Area, Oklahoma City, Oklahoma
postcontent: First, I am NOT the guy posting warnings about buying used body armor.  But he speaks the truth!!  Kevlar degrades with heat, moisture and most specifically - sweat.  You CAN run a vest past the expiration dates given by the manufacturer and still receive some protection from the panels.  But only if the vest has spent most of its time hanging in a closet or riding around in the back seat of a scout car.  If you are looking at used body armor, take a look at the ballistic panels inside the carrier.  If they are soiled, stained and discolored - DON'T FREAKING BUY IT! Some newer vests have the panels heat-sealed inside plastic covers that repel moisture.  They will last longer than older vests with panels sewn inside cloth wraps.  Still, Kevlar will degrade as a natural process.  So even a clean panel (or one sealed inside a plastic cover) that's five years past the expiration date wont provide the protection reflected on the tag.  If you are playing paintball, any old rotted body armor should do the trick.  If you are playing with actual bullets (or the other guy is) I would be very careful what I wore - and I am, just ordered a new vest myself.

title: For Sale/Trade:  Lot for trade/sale at Lake Sherwood Estates
location: Lake Sherwood Estates, St. Louis, Missouri
postcontent:
Come out to Lake Sherwood Estates private community and enjoy the multiple lakes to swim, fish, boat or just relax. The main lake allows small boats up to 20' and pontoons to 24'. Or kayak and canoe the coves or the swim docks by the Dam. There is a beach with a roped off swim area, life guards and security. They have a pool, club house, seasonal cafe, sand volleyball, Marina and picnic areas throughout. The 15 acre and smaller lakes allow electric powered fishing boats, kayaks, canoes, etc. Guard shack and patrols keep the place quiet and relaxing and your lot and boat safe. No back trails with ATV's screaming around, etc. 

I bought a .25 acre lot to allow my family and friends to come enjoy the lake, beach, fishing and campground over a year ago. My Mom loved it so much she bought a lot also. So I am putting this one up for trade or sale so you and yours can enjoy as well. All my taxes $60 a year, and my monthly assessment $90 a month (or going out to dinner with two kids twice, lol) are all current and paid up. You can also pay it quarterly and yearly to save a few dollars. I am not dumping my debt or problems, we love the place! But why have two family members pay the assesments? Alot of lot only owners bought steep unbuildable lots and put an APPROVED shed or gazebo up to just enjoy the place without building a home, no moblie homes or RV's allowed. Our lot has the perfect grade for a walkout and nice yard. The lot next door 1598 Marion owned by Lake Sherwood Estates has an asking price of $11,000.00 and a drainage ditch down the middle?!? The brick ranch across the street was going for $180,000.00 last year. 

My lot 1599 Marion has a trade value of $1750.00 and a cash value of $1500.00 . Why so cheap, whats wrong with it? NOTHING. Just passing on the deal I got, that is typical asking price unless it is MAIN or secondary lake side property. Some are cheaper and further from the lake or almost have a cliff side slope. Or some owe so many back taxes and assesments they can't dig out. I will still be at the beach and enjoying the place this year and many more. But using Mom's guest list and gate pass to get in. So why pay twice??

Why take a once a year vacation when you can do it every weekend? Pack the cooler and beach gear and come enjoy, a boat is not necessary but a fishing pole helps.  It is located close the intersection of Hwy T and Hwy D. Close to Wentzville, Wright City, Warrenton, Washington, New Melle, etc. It takes us 35min from driveway to beach down Hwy 70.
